{"cursor":"27449","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Solid modeling' (or 'modelling') is a consistent set of principles for\nmathematical and computer modeling of three-dimensional solids. Solid modeling\nis distinguished from related areas of geometric modeling and computer graphics\nby its emphasis on physical fidelity.\nTogether, the principles of geometric and solid modeling form the foundation of\ncomputer-aided design and in general support the creation, exchange,\nvisualization, animation, interrogation, and annotation of digital models of\nphysical objects.\n","linknr":302,"url":"Solid_modelling","recorded":1362374832,"links":23,"instances":["engineering","topology","mathematics","topology","computer_science","cad_program","mathematical_logic","topology","topology","mathematics","image_processing","topology","physics","mathematics","geometry","mathematics","topology"],"pdf":[],"categories":["3D computer graphics","Computer-aided design","Euclidean solid geometry"],"headings":["Overview","Mathematical foundations","Solid representation schemes","History of solid modelers","Computer-aided design","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0f/Jack-in-cube_solid_model%2C_light_background.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/Regularize1.png/450px-Regularize1.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/9/9/499762b6bcdfc81f4d46843524c1c096.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/c/5/3c59d219f02c3254b0e53496b44b88b2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/8/1/581d8a624953ec04ccd934d0603488ec.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/a/3/ea3e90fa1abc7bb27a7d599c6562d303.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50p